"The humanitarian situation in Gaza was desperate before the last hostilities. Now it's catastrophic. The world must do more." This is read in a joint communiqué of five UN agencies – for international development (
), for sexual and reproductive health (
), for children (
), for food assistance in emergencies (
) and the World Health Organization (WHO).
"Thousands of thousands of people are displaced and cannot cook, nor buy food safely," write the five agencies. They call for a ceasefire "immediate", because "the hospitals are overloaded with victims. The civilian population has more and more difficulty in accessing essential food supplies" and Palestinian children and girls "moving at an impressive pace". On Saturday, the Palestinian Government has announced that 1'756 have died so far.
On the edge of the conference on the Middle East on Saturday in Cairo, the UN humanitarian emergency aid coordinator Martin Griffiths said that four WHO-organized trucks are directed to Gaza with medical material for injured people and suffering from chronic diseases. In addition to the drugs, he said, the WHO trucks would contain additional essential goods for tens of thousands of people in difficulty. Saturday, moreover, would land in Egypt a UN aircraft with curtains of fortune, stocks of drinking water and disinfectants, instruments for operating rooms. The WHO spokesman pointed out that there are 170 trucks loaded and ready to bring to the people of Gaza humanitarian auts - stopped at the Rafah Pass. On Saturday, 20 were allowed to cross the border with Palestinian Territories.
